Product Segmentation Summary

Premium Skincare – “A-items”: highest margin, demand accelerating (North, East), critically low cover (4-12 days), supply delay in East; must be protected.
Premium Makeup – “B-items”: good margin, growth in North/East, adequate but tightening cover (9-15 days); requires standard but well-controlled replenishment.
Budget Skincare – “C-items”: strategic to keep shelf presence, especially in the low-sales cluster (frequent stock-outs, only 5 days cover). Other regions are over-stocked (18-26 days).
Budget Makeup – “D-items”: demand falling in every region, very high cover (25-34 days). Represents the largest excess-inventory risk.
High-Priority Products (service first, higher safety stock, weekly review) • Premium Skincare (all regions) – Demand signal: +12-15 % Q/Q in North, +20 % in East, stable elsewhere. – Service risk: only 4-5 days cover in North/East and 7-day inbound delay (East). – Policy: target 18-20 days safety stock, weekly forecast refresh, automatic expedite trigger at 10 days cover. • Premium Makeup in North & East – Rising demand (North +9 %, East +11 %). Days cover 9-10. – Policy: 14-day safety stock, weekly review, maintain dual sourcing to avoid the delays seen in skincare.

Medium-Priority Products (standard replenishment, bi-weekly review) • Premium Makeup in South & West – Stable demand, 14-15 days cover is sufficient; hold current reorder points. • Budget Skincare in Low-Sales Cluster – Essential for brand presence; only 5 days cover with frequent stock-outs. – Replenish by re-allocating excess from West (26 days) & East (22 days) before placing new PO’s. • Budget Skincare in North/South/East/West – Demand flat to declining, but still relevant. Current 18-26 days cover; freeze new orders until stock <12 days.

Low-Priority Products (selective stocking, monthly review, run-down plan) • Budget Makeup (all regions) – Demand falling everywhere (-8 % to -12 % Q/Q). Inventory cover 25-34 days. – Actions: cancel open PO’s, initiate sell-off or promotion, cut target cover to 10-12 days, consider SKU rationalisation.

Recommended Next Actions Immediate (next 7 days) • Expedite the 300 delayed Premium Skincare units to East and pull 120 units from South & West to North to lift cover above 12 days in the two fastest-growing regions.

Medium-term (next 30 days) • Implement differentiated min / max parameters in the ERP: – Premium categories: Min 12, Max 24 days. – Budget skincare: Min 6, Max 15 days (except low-sales cluster Min 10, Max 20). – Budget makeup: Min 5, Max 12 days. Include a weekly “ABC” report so planners and sales see the same priority codes.

Highest-priority stock policy decision • Elevate Premium Skincare to “service-critical” with a mandatory 18-day safety stock and weekly executive review because it drives the highest gross margin and is currently the most supply-constrained.

Cross-functional issue to coordinate • Budget Makeup exit / run-down strategy – Supply Chain must align with Sales & Inventory Control on markdown budgets, promotion calendar, and SKU retirement dates to prevent write-offs while clearing the 25-34 days of excess stock.
